{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}
'''Geoffrey Haydon Manning''' (1926 – 12 September 2018) was an Australian author and historian, commonly known as Geoff Manning, known particularly for his books on South Australian placenames: first edition ''Romance of Place Names of South Australia'' 1986 followed by ''Manning's Place Names of South Australia'' 1990 and his final illustrated edition of 1,400 pages, ''The Place Names Of Our Land: A South Australian Anthology''.

==History==
Manning was born in [[Waikerie, South Australia]], a son of carpenter Richard Baker Manning (1896–1936) and his wife Grace Maud Manning, née Hein (1901– ).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geoffmanning.net.au/index.html|title=Geoff Manning: Insight|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref>

He was employed by the [[Savings Bank of South Australia]] until his retirement in 1982, since when he has written on local history.
His fully indexed work on South Australian placenames has been digitized by the [[State Library of South Australia]] and is, with his collection of significant articles from South Australian newspapers [http://www.slsa.sa.gov.au/manning/search.html freely available on-line]. His works on South Australian placenames contains much information supplemental to, and correcting, the much earlier ''Nomenclature of South Australia'' (1908) by [[Rodney Cockburn]] (1877–1932) and ''What's in a Name'', a revised edition by his son Stewart Cockburn.

==Family==
[[Haydon R. Manning]], political scientist of [[Flinders University]], is a son.

